'''Hampshire and Isle of Wight Air Ambulance''' is an [[air ambulance]] service serving the counties of [[Hampshire]] and [[Isle of Wight]] in [[Southern England]], [[United Kingdom]]. It is one of twenty-five [[Air Ambulances in the United Kingdom|air ambulance services in the United Kingdom]].



The service began operating on 1 July 2007 and has flown over 3,400 missions. The charity's head office is located at 4 Kings Park Road, [[Southampton]] and the helicopter is based at [[Thruxton, Hampshire|Thruxton]] airfield near [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiow-airambulance.org.uk/page.cfm/about-us |title=About Us — Hampshire & Isle of Wight Air Ambulance |publisher=Hiow-airambulance.org.uk |date=2007-07-01 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>

==Crew==


The service covers the counties of Hampshire and Isle of Wight, and responds where required to [[traffic collision]]s, sporting accidents, collapses, and other incidents. It may conduct helicopter emergency medical service (HEMS) during the daytime only, but may carry out non-emergency patient transfers between approved lit sites during both daylight and night-time hours.

The air ambulance costs around £125,000 per month to operate efficiently and successfully.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiow-airambulance.org.uk/page.cfm/about-us/the-service |title=The Service — Hampshire & Isle of Wight Air Ambulance |publisher=Hiow-airambulance.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>

==Helicopter==
The current helicopter is a twin-engined [[Eurocopter EC135]], a type often utilised as an air ambulance. It is usually airborne within four minutes and typically flies at 140&nbsp;mph, making it capable of reaching most locations in Hampshire within fifteen minutes, though flights to the Isle of Wight may take longer.

The Eurocopter EC135 replaced its predecessor, a 33-year-old [[MBB Bo 105]], in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/8422316.New_chopper_for_air_ambulance/ |title=Hampshire and Isle of Wight Air Ambulance celebrate new helicopter (From Daily Echo) |publisher=Dailyecho.co.uk |date=2010-09-30 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref> The EC135 can carry a crew of up to four, but typically carries two [[paramedic]]s and one pilot. An additional doctor or family member of the patient may occupy the fourth seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiow-airambulance.org.uk/page.cfm/about-us/the-helicopter-1 |title=The Helicopter — Hampshire & Isle of Wight Air Ambulance |publisher=Hiow-airambulance.org.uk |date=2010-09-29 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>

==Crew==
The air ambulance is crewed by one of two pilots and typically two of ten paramedics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiow-airambulance.org.uk/page.cfm/about-us/the-helicopter |title=The Crew — Hampshire & Isle of Wight Air Ambulance |publisher=Hiow-airambulance.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>

